Extremely edge-case annotation; copy pasting notes on it here:

Very confused as to how to annotate this. The Greek here is Λύκαια, which Scaife identifies as the Lycaea, a festival celebrating Zeus Lycaea. Lycaea the festival has an Encyclopaedia Britannica entry, albeit very brief, but there is no corresponding Wikipedia entry (for the festival; there is one for a town of the same name), though it is heavily referenced in the Mount Lykaion and Lycaon (king of Arcadia). So, my best thought would be to either tag it as .event (but that seems more for one time big things, not recurring festivals) or as .miscellaneous, with either optionally having a .mythological tag on it. However, if it comes from Mt Lykaion (or even the town Lycaea), then maybe “Lycaean” would be better tagged as a collective.ethnic?

Case study because this town (and general area of the map) gave me huge trouble the first time around.  This town is only attested to in Xenophon, and only has an entry in the Brill encyclopaedia, which you have to pay for, and also doesn't give any more information beyond what's evident in this text.

Case study and ambiguous for the exact same reasons as Ceramon-agora, so see that note. May be a small town on the plains of the river Caystrus, (pedion [πεδίον] just means plain); Caystrus river plain is attested to in Homer, Strabo, Cicero, though not with a town mentioned
Another lost city, similar to Caystru-pedion and such. Not to be confused with Thymbra; I made that mistake before
This spring of water is, as far as I can tell, literally only referenced in Xenophon, with no real-world corroboration or geo-reference point available
While not capitalized in English, it is in the Greek (τὸν Σάτυρον), and it refers to a very specific entity, so I went ahead and annotated it

Pleiades is being werid and putting Soli on Cypress, but it most cetainly wasn't there. It was in the modern day city of Mersin. Still using the Pleiades entry for the data, but must be manually corrected.
Annotated the whole string since Pyramus on its own would more likely refer to the mythological figure

Not the Caresus, since that's near Troy on the complete other side of Anatolia.  Also not the Orontes river, since that flows and empites out south of the pass. Since it's said to flow through the Gates between Cilicia and Syria, it may have been a small stream that's since dried up? Then again, it gives the width as a plethron (~33.7 yrds), which isn't crazy small, but also not the biggest in this text. Also, the coastline in this area has probably changed a lot, just based on the description he gives.

COMMENTS: It may be the Chalos/Belus ( the Greek name given is Χάλον), which seems to be in the right spot, but I cannot for the life of me figure out why the Belus is called Chalos, especially since the wikipedia page for Belus redirects to Na'aman, which is in Israel. The actual location is unknown.  Another lost city. The actual Araxes (in Iran) is way too far out of the way for where Xenophon is. Farrell (1961) and Engles (1980) argue that Xenophon went to modern day Carchemish (Thapsacus), then crossed at the Balikh, and the Balikh fits on the map.
Modern day called the Khabur river, a tributary of the Euphrates

This is absolutely not the Orontas I, the satrap that shows up later in this book and the rest of the text. I have no idea why Xenophon doesn't distinguish between them, but here we are.  No wikipedia page about this Orontas, but there is an Encyclopaedia Iranica page on the name, which this entity is mentioned as the first instance. There's also a neat article of JSTOR about his trial.


As of of right now, I tagged him orontas_traitor so as to differentiate the two, and haven't linked the Encyclopaedia Iranica article yet
